For this task, create a network security group (NSG) with the following requirements:

Name of the NSG should be xfusion-nsg.

Add an inbound security rule named Allow-HTTP for HTTP service on port 80, with the source CIDR range of 0.0.0.0/0.

Add another inbound security rule named Allow-SSH for SSH service on port 22, with the source CIDR range of 0.0.0.0/0.

Azure Portal Solution
Go to the Azure Portal: Open Azure Portal.
Navigate to Network Security Groups:
In the left-hand menu, search for "Network Security Groups" and select it.
Click "+ Create" to create a new NSG.
Configure the NSG:
Subscription: Choose your appropriate subscription.
Resource Group: Select the existing resource group.
NSG Name: Set the name to xfusion-nsg.
Region: Choose the region, such as East US.
Add Inbound Security Rules:
After creating the NSG, go to the Inbound security rules section.
Click "+ Add" to create a new rule.
For HTTP (Port 80):
Name: Allow-HTTP
Protocol: TCP
Port Range: 80
Source: Any
Source IP Range: 0.0.0.0/0
Action: Allow
Priority: 1000
For SSH (Port 22):
Name: Allow-SSH
Protocol: TCP
Port Range: 22
Source: Any
Source IP Range: 0.0.0.0/0
Action: Allow
Priority: 1010
Save the Rules:
Click Add to save both rules.


CLI Solution
Create the NSG with the name xfusion-nsg:
az network nsg create \
  --resource-group <your-resource-group> \
  --name xfusion-nsg \
  --location eastus
Explanation:
--resource-group: Replace <your-resource-group> with the name of your resource group.
--name: Specifies the name of the NSG as xfusion-nsg.
--location: Sets the region for the NSG (e.g., eastus).
Add an inbound security rule for HTTP (port 80):
az network nsg rule create \
  --resource-group <your-resource-group> \
  --nsg-name xfusion-nsg \
  --name Allow-HTTP \
  --protocol tcp \
  --priority 1000 \
  --destination-port-ranges 80 \
  --access Allow \
  --direction Inbound \
  --source-address-prefixes 0.0.0.0/0
Explanation:
--name Allow-HTTP: Name of the security rule.
--destination-port-ranges 80: The rule allows traffic on port 80 (HTTP).
--source-address-prefixes 0.0.0.0/0: This allows traffic from any source IP address.
--priority 1000: The priority value. Lower numbers have higher priority.
Add an inbound security rule for SSH (port 22):
az network nsg rule create \
  --resource-group <your-resource-group> \
  --nsg-name xfusion-nsg \
  --name Allow-SSH \
  --protocol tcp \
  --priority 1010 \
  --destination-port-ranges 22 \
  --access Allow \
  --direction Inbound \
  --source-address-prefixes 0.0.0.0/0
Explanation:
--name Allow-SSH: Name of the security rule.
--destination-port-ranges 22: The rule allows traffic on port 22 (SSH).
--source-address-prefixes 0.0.0.0/0: This allows traffic from any source IP address.
--priority 1010: The priority value for this rule.
